Here's a practical approach:

## 1. Define theme resource dictionaries

Create separate XAML files for each theme:

**Themes/LightTheme.xaml**
```xml
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

**Themes/DarkTheme.xaml**
```xml
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#1E1E1E</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#F0F0F0</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#4CC2FF</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

**Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml**
```xml
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#000000</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#FFFF00</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

## 2. Create a theme service

```csharp
public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(string themeName)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove the current theme dictionary (keep other shared resources)
        var existing = mergedDicts.FirstOrDefault(d => d.Source?.OriginalString.Contains("Theme") == true);
        if (existing != null)
            mergedDicts.Remove(existing);

        var theme = themeName switch
        {
            "Dark" => new DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast" => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _ => new LightTheme()
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(theme);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", themeName);
    }
}
```

## 3. Load the saved theme at startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:
```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light");
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(saved);
}
```

## 4. Use `DynamicResource` in your UI

This is critical — `StaticResource` won't update at runtime:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource TextPrimary}" Text="Hello" />
    <Button BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource AccentColor}" Text="Click" />
</ContentPage>
```

## 5. Settings page picker

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Theme"
        ItemsSource="{Binding Themes}"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged" />
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    var selected = ThemePicker.SelectedItem as string;
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(selected!);
}
```

**Key points:**
- Always use `DynamicResource` so controls react to dictionary swaps.
- Use `Preferences` to persist the user's choice across sessions.
- The swap is instant — no restart needed.
